To unzip a file into your current working directory, you actually dont need to specify a destination at allby default, unzip extracts the contents into the directory where you run the command. Here are the two common forms:

  • Extract into the current directory:

    unzip filename.zip

    This will create the contained files and folders right where you are.

  • Extract into a specific directory:

    unzip filename.zip -d /path/to/target

    Replace /path/to/target with the absolute or relative path of the directory you want to extract to. If you really want to be explicit about the current directory, you can use -d . (the dot represents the current directory), but its optional.

When a .zip archive contains its own toplevel folder (like EverLightOS/), unzip will faithfully recreate that folder. There isnt a builtin flag to strip just the first path component, but there are two common ways to achieve what you want:

  1. Extract normally, move, then remove the wrapper folder:

    # extract the zip (creates EverLightOS/ in the current dir)
unzip EverLightOS_scaffold.zip

# move everything inside EverLightOS into the current directory
mv EverLightOS/* .

# remove the now-empty top-level directory
rmdir EverLightOS

    This preserves the directory structure (core/, styles/, etc.) but removes the extra toplevel wrapper.

  2. Use the -j (junk paths) flag to flatten everything (not recommended if you need subfolders):

    unzip -j EverLightOS_scaffold.zip

    With -j, all files are dumped into the current directory and any subdirectory structure is discarded. Thats usually only useful when there are no nested folders you want to keep.

If youre on a system with BSD tar (Git Bash typically includes it), theres also a oneliner that strips just the first directory layer:

bsdtar -xf EverLightOS_scaffold.zip --strip-components=1

Any of these approaches will avoid creating a nested EverLightOS/ directory and instead place the contents directly in your working folder.

# Make sure youre up to date and on the main branch
